                        <div id="content" class="hfeed">
                            <article class="post-153583 post type-post status-publish hentry category-private-lives tag-nantucket-mass tag-tennis des-tennis geo-nantucket-mass news_keywords-nantucket news_keywords-tennis" id="post-153583">
                                <header class="postHeader">
                                    <div class="postKicker">
                                        <span class="kicker"><a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/?module=BlogCategory&amp;version=Blog Post&amp;action=Click&amp;contentCollection=Opinion&amp;pgtype=Blogs&amp;region=Header">Private Lives</a></span>
                                    </div>
                                    <h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">The Tennis Pro&#x2019;s Daughter</h1>
                                    <div class="story-meta-footer">
                                        <address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Caroline Hamilton			</address>
                                        <!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-07-10T00:00:10+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">July 9, 2014 8:00 pm</time>
                                        <!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">July 9, 2014 8:00 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
                                    </div>
                                </header>
                                <div class="entry-content">
                                    <div class="inlineModule">
                                        <div class="entry">
                                            <div class="thumb"><img alt="Private Lives" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/firstperson/firstperson45.png" width="50" height="50"></div>
                                            <p class="summary"> <a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/">Private Lives:</a> Personal essays on the news of the world and the news of our lives.
                                            </p>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For 13 summers, my father worked as the tennis pro at a yacht club on Nantucket. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">During the school year, Dad coached varsity tennis for a university in Boston, and we lived in nearby Belmont, an intellectual suburb peppered with hockey heroes and Mormons. I rode the school bus with a family of blue-eyed
                                        angels who wouldn&#x2019;t play spin the bottle. Our life was comfortable and ordinary, filled with sports practices and brown-bag lunches. The only thing special about me was that I had red hair. And that I went
                                        to Nantucket. <span id="more-153583"></span></p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Every summer, my older brother, Jeffrey, and I woke in our staff cottage to the whistle of ferries and the scent of honeysuckle. In the mornings, while Dad was teaching lessons, we sailed dinghies in the harbor and
                                        played badminton in the clubhouse. In the afternoons, we navigated riptides and wandered the wharves. &#x201C;I&#x2019;m going to have one like that,&#x201D; Jeffrey would say, pointing to a houseboat where crystal
                                        glasses sparkled on a wet bar.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the heat of July, Dad often proposed challenge matches between Jeffrey and the other young tennis players at the club. The goal was to &#x201C;climb the ladder&#x201D; and become the champion by the end of the summer.
                                        Before the matches, Dad shook hands with the other kids&#x2019; fathers &#x2014; businessmen with pink golf shirts, dark sunglasses and crisp New England attitudes &#x2014; and smiled. But when a swanlike girl showed
                                        up in pearl earrings and a white pleated skirt to play Jeffrey, it felt like more than a game. I sat in the stands wearing hand-me-down Umbro shorts, nervously swinging my feet. When she won with a final topspin
                                        ace, Dad&#x2019;s shoulders fell, but he put his hand on Jeffrey&#x2019;s back and talked about a rematch. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On Saturday nights, the yacht club families invited us to picnics. We drove our old station wagon to the edge of the beach and then caught a ride in someone else&#x2019;s four-wheel-drive, flying through the deep sand.
                                        On Smith&#x2019;s Point, where the world was three-quarters sky and one-quarter land, the men grilled bluefish and the women sipped chardonnay, their charm bracelets jangling. We might have been more realistic about
                                        our sense of belonging had the whole scene not been heavily intoxicating: Jeffrey was flying a kite with the other boys, Dad was yelling something encouraging and Mom&#x2019;s crazy hair was flying in the wind.</p>
                                    <div class="w480">
                                        <figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/09/opinion/0709PRIVATELIVES/0709PRIVATELIVES-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject"
                                            role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span>
                                            <div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/09/opinion/0709PRIVATELIVES/0709PRIVATELIVES-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/09/opinion/0709PRIVATELIVES/0709PRIVATELIVES-blog480.jpg"
                                                    id="100000002991592" width="480" height="560" alt="">
                                                <meta itemprop="height" content="560">
                                                <meta itemprop="width" content="480">
                                            </div>
                                            <figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Sophia Foster-Dimino</span>
                                            </figcaption>
                                        </figure>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I was old enough in the summer after fifth grade to have a crush on a Connecticut kid I&#x2019;ll call Harper. Harper had blue eyes, blond hair and a band of freckles across his nose. Once, when I was hitting forehands
                                        against the splintered backboard, he parked his bike behind the fence and said, &#x201C;You&#x2019;re the best girl I know.&#x201D; I knew he meant at tennis, but I pretended he meant it generally, repeating it
                                        to myself as I twisted around in my sandy sheets that night. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Then, on the ferry ride to our tennis match against Martha&#x2019;s Vineyard, he came out to the windy deck where I was eating a blueberry muffin, and asked, &#x201C;Bite?&#x201D; </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;O.K.,&#x201D; I said, and blushed as he came toward me with his front teeth. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A few weeks later, Harper called me. &#x201C;Do you want to play with me in the junior mixed-doubles tournament?&#x201D; he asked. &#x201C;I need a partner.&#x201D; Heart pounding, I wrote my name next to his on the
                                        club&#x2019;s bulletin board. But a few days later, my name was missing. I was gently told by my mother, who had been reminded by someone at the club, that the tournament was for members only.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I didn&#x2019;t see Harper again.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We left Nantucket in the Labor Day fog, dreading the school year. Jeffrey threw pennies over the deck as the ferry rounded the corner at Brant Point Lighthouse, making the traditional &#x201C;wish to come back.&#x201D;
                                        I sat inside by myself and watched the island disappear.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">One night that winter, I must have been 11, Dad took a phone call. In the family meeting that followed, Jeffrey and I learned that there was no longer a position for him at the club. We would not be returning to Nantucket
                                        that summer.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;What about next year?&#x201D; Jeffrey asked.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;I don&#x2019;t think so,&#x201D; my mom answered.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I spent the summer after sixth grade hanging around a public swimming pool with one of my local friends. The locker room smelled like mildew and the concrete burned the bottoms of my feet. Eating frozen chicken fingers
                                        a little too close to the freeway, I remembered the piano music and flapping flags of Nantucket. It seemed like something out of a storybook.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Dad went on to coach at other clubs, camps and universities, even earning N.C.A.A. coach of the year in his division. Tennis continued to be our golden ticket, but I was now aware of its limitations. Some days we lived
                                        like royalty, rubbing shoulders with the elite; other days, we were lightly reminded that we couldn&#x2019;t order from the snack bar. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the years after college, it seemed as if everyone I knew was having weddings on Nantucket. My Facebook page filled up with their windswept entrances and exits. They carried bouquets of hydrangeas out of my favorite
                                        white-steepled church. I felt both intimately near them and impossibly far away. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I returned to the island only a few times over the years, always unsure of my relationship with the place. I rushed to visit my favorite beaches and shops, only to prickle with resentment on cattailed paths and in rose-covered
                                        doorways. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But when I finally took my husband to Nantucket for the first time, I saw everything newly through his eyes, and the view of the harbor from the ferry left me short of breath. I pointed out the beaches where Mom and
                                        I had collected scallop shells and the fields where Jeffrey and I fed rabbits. Widow&#x2019;s walks topped the shingled houses on the hill. It was still so beautiful. It was like encountering the person who first
                                        broke your heart, and trying to smile.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The boat slowed and reverberated as we entered the harbor, and there were the red clay courts where Dad had taught tennis, his calves as big as grapefruits and his nose covered in zinc oxide. There was the clubhouse
                                        where my name had been erased.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In a way, Dad&#x2019;s experience on Nantucket was the best coaching of all. It taught me that I was not entitled to a vacation home or a round-trip ticket to the earth&#x2019;s wild edge. And in losing those luxuries,
                                        I realized there were other, intangible things that could not be taken from me: memory, tennis, love. Feeling the salt on my face and the cobblestones beneath my feet again, a sense of belonging blossomed within
                                        me. It sprang out of a deep friendship with myself, and invited me to ignore the invisible ladders life tempts us to climb. </p>
                                    <hr>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Caroline Hamilton is a writer in New York. </em></p>
                                    <footer class="story-footer">
                                        <div class="story-meta">
                                            <p class="story-print-citation">A version of this article appears in print on 07/13/2014, on page <span itemprop="printSection">SR</span><span itemprop="printPage">8</span> of the <span itemprop="printEdition">NewYork</span> edition with the
                                                headline: The Tennis Pro&#x2019;s Daughter.</p>
                                        </div>
                                    </footer>
